 ethnographic and interdisciplinary approach to explore the writings and texts of dark journeys and travels. In traveling over the dead, amongst the dying, and alongside the suffering, the authors give us a tour of humanity’s violence and misery. And yet, from this dark side, there comes great beauty and poignancy in the characterization of plight; creativity in the comic, graphic, and graffiti sketches and comments on life; and the sense of profound and spiritual journeys being undertaken, recorded, and memorialized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aSocial problems. 0aTourismxPsychological aspects. 0aTourismxSocial aspects. 0aTravelxPsychological aspects. 7aTravel / Essays & Travelogues.2bisacsh1 aCooke, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHepburn, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIles, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoffat, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagle, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkinner, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkinner, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWalker, Tristram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745876640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857458766423Coveruht